{"id": 231215988, "title": "Katsina To Embrace E-Governance Initiatives For Development", "text": "KATSINA \u2013 The Katsina State Directorate of Information and Communication Technology, KATDICT, complex has been commissioned to embrace digital innovation and modernizing technological infrastructure in the state. Governor Dikko Umaru Radda, in his address shortly after commissioning the directorate complex in Katsina on Friday, unveiled four key projects expected to spearhead the state\u2019s digital transformation. He said the initiatives is aimed atenhancing connectivity of the Katsina Broadband Masterplan to achieve penetration across the state, foster economic growth and improve communication. According to him, towards fostering data-driven governance, the Katsina Data Revolution Master plan would prioritize data collection and analysis to ensure effective decision-making at all levels of government. The Governor added that, to further improve public service delivery, it would also focus on modernizing government processes with advanced technology aimed at increasing efficiency, enhance service standards and improve accessibility for the people. \u201cThese projects will be guided by the KATDICT Strategic Blueprint and comprehensive plan outlines of the government\u2019s digital transformation strategy for 2023-2027 to provide a clear roadmap for the state\u2019s digital future\u201d. Radda commended Naufal Ahmad,the Director-General of KATDICT for driving the project to completion, emphasizing that, it has shown the importance of young leadership in government. \u201cThe past ten months have been a testament to the value of young people in strategic positions. They bring innovation and dynamic skills to their roles and their dedication is evident in this achievement.\u201d On the success of the FAGO PAY initiative, the Governor noted that, since its launch in October 2023, it has facilitated over one billion naira (approximately 730 million US dollars) in transactions, adding that, this initiative demonstrates the potential of e-governance to deliver enormous benefits for the people of the state. While pledging his administration\u2019s continued support to the ICT Directorate, he enjoined FAGO PAY to collaborate with the Katsina State Development Agency (KASEDA) to explore ways to simplify account opening procedures for aspiring entrepreneurs. Governor Radda then reiterated his administration\u2019s commitment to ICT and digital transformation, saying, \u201cIn today\u2019s world, digital technologies are essential. We are dedicated to integrating these technologies into every aspect of our operations to deliver efficient and effective services to the people of the state.\u201d Naufal Ahmad, the Director General of KATDICT, earlier, said the institute has concluded plans to equip civil servants with the digital skills necessary to operate the new technologies effectively. Ahmad however assured the public of full internet connectivity across the state by the end of 2027, also promised that, the twelve different policies and guidelines established to ensure ICT advancements would benefit all citizens of the state.Katsina To Embrace E-Governance Initiatives For DevelopmentSEGUN OLANIYAN KATSINAThe Katsina State Directorate of Information and Communication Technology KATDICT, complex has been commissioned to embrace digital innovation and modernizing technological infrastructure in the state.Governor Dikko Umaru Radda, in his address shortly after commissioning the directorate complex in Katsina on Friday, unveiled four key projects expected to spearhead the state\u2019s digital transformation. He said the initiatives is aimed atenhancing connectivity of the Katsina Broadband Masterplan to achieve penetration across the state, foster economic growth and improve communication.According to him, towards fostering data-driven governance, the Katsina Data Revolution Master plan would prioritize data collection and analysis to e